AB  - The paper uses U.S. data to reconsider the Kuznets hypothesis of sectoral convergence in levels of real product per worker. It shows a significant increase in the intersectoral inequality ratio in 1948–1982. The low productivity pure services play a role symmetrical to that of agriculture in developing countries, but their contribution to employment and to overall inequality increases over time. The findings suggest a revised view of product and employment accounts.
